    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start. I want to make sure my students understand *why* this is so important. Like, why do we actually need \"substantive\" due process? Isn't \"procedural\" due process—just making sure the legal steps are followed correctly—enough to protect people? Why is the substantive version seen as the more essential one for actual justice?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Substantive due process is crucial because it goes beyond the basic legal procedures and ensures that the government's actions are fair and just, protecting fundamental rights that are essential to individual freedom and dignity. While procedural due process focuses on the fairness of legal processes, substantive due process addresses whether the laws themselves are just. It's seen as more essential because without it, the government could pass laws that, on the surface, seem fair in procedure but actually infringe upon fundamental personal liberties. Substantive due process acts as a safeguard, ensuring that laws don't just follow a fair process but are also just and equitable in protecting our most intrinsic rights.",
      "source": "target",
