    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I see. So you're saying the procedural side is kind of just a formality, whereas substantive due process is where the real protection of rights happens. Some legal scholars argue that substantive due process is actually pretty problematic because it lets judges basically make up new rights based on their own personal values rather than sticking to the actual text of the Constitution. Do you think those critics have a point, or is their view just outdated?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The critics of substantive due process do raise valid concerns. They argue that it can lead to judicial activism, where judges impose their personal values on the Constitution, potentially creating rights that aren't grounded in the text or original intent of the Founders. This can be seen as undermining the democratic process, as it shifts the power to define rights from elected representatives to unelected judges. While some view this approach as necessary for progress, others see it as a departure from the Constitution's original purpose. It's a complex issue, and this debate reflects broader tensions between a living Constitution and a more originalist or textualist interpretation. Each perspective has its merits, and the discussion around substantive due process continues to evolve as society changes.",
      "source": "target",
